If $\boldsymbol{x} \in \mathbb{R}^d$ and if $A$ is a subset of $\mathbb{R}^d$, the following two conditions are equivalent:
(i) $\boldsymbol{x}$ is a limit point of $A$;
(ii) there is a sequence $(\boldsymbol{x}_n)$ in $A$ such that $\lim_{n \to \infty} \boldsymbol{x}_n = \boldsymbol{x}$.

The following conditions on a subset $A$ of $\mathbb{R}^d$ are equivalent:
(i) $A$ is closed.
(ii) $\operatorname{der}(A) \subseteq A$, i.e., $A$ contains all of its cluster points;
(iii) $\operatorname{bd}(A) \subseteq A$, i.e., $A$ contains all of its boundary points;
(iv) $\operatorname{cl}(A) \subseteq A$, i.e., $A$ contains all of its limit points;
(v) if $(\boldsymbol{x}_n)$ is any convergent sequence in $A$, then $\lim_{n \to \infty} \boldsymbol{x}_n \in A$.

The following two conditions are equivalent for a subset $A \subseteq \mathbb{R}^d$:
(i) $A$ is closed and bounded;
(ii) every sequence in $A$ has a subsequence that converges to a point in $A$.

For any nonempty set $A$, any point $\boldsymbol{a} \in A$, and any real-valued function $f$ with domain $A$, the following are equivalent:
(i) for each point $\boldsymbol{a} \in A$ and each $\epsilon > 0$, there is a $\delta > 0$ such that $|f(\boldsymbol{x}) - f(\boldsymbol{a})| < \epsilon$ for all $\boldsymbol{x} \in A \cap B_\delta(\boldsymbol{a})$;
(ii) if $(\boldsymbol{a_n})$ is a sequence in $A$ that converges to $\boldsymbol{a}$, then $\lim_{n \to \infty} f(\boldsymbol{a_n}) = f(\boldsymbol{a})$.

For a subset $A \subseteq \mathbb{R}^d$, the following three conditions are equivalent:
(i) $A$ is closed and bounded;
(ii) every sequence in $A$ has a subsequence converging to a point in $A$;
(iii) every open covering of $A$ has a finite subcover.
